Explanation:

Step-by-step reasoning:
- The controller App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\UserPostController@index returns PostResource::collection(...) of a paginated query: $user->posts()->latest()->paginate($request->input('limit', 20)).
- When a JsonResource collection wraps a LengthAwarePaginator in Laravel, the usual JSON structure is an object with keys "data" (array of resource objects), "links" (pagination links), and "meta" (pagination metadata). I used that structure for the 200 response schema.
- The Post resource (app/Http/Resources/Post.php) defines the fields returned for each post. I inspected that file and derived the properties and their basic types:
  - id (integer)
  - title (string)
  - slug (string)
  - content (string)
  - posted_at (ISO 8601 datetime string)
  - author_id (integer)
  - comments_count (integer)
  - thumbnail_url (string when present)
  - thumb_thumbnail_url (string when present)
- For the pagination "links" and "meta" objects I used the typical Laravel paginator response shape: links: {first,last,prev,next} and meta: {current_page,from,last_page,links (array of {url,label,active}), path, per_page, to, total}.
- Because the controller type-hints User $user, route-model binding in Laravel will produce a 404 if the user does not exist; I included a 404 response object with a simple error message schema.
- The output is a JSON dictionary of Response Objects (Swagger 2.0 style) for the GET /v1/users/{user}/posts endpoint. I did not use $ref references and kept all schemas inline.

